{"id":"orch-go-4kjf","title":"Daemon writes status file on each poll cycle","description":"Add daemon status file writing to polling loop. Write ~/.orch/daemon-status.json with: {capacity: {max, active, available}, last_poll, last_spawn, ready_count, status: running|stalled}. Use atomic write (temp + rename). This enables serve.go to expose daemon health without IPC.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-26T09:34:06.279664-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-26T12:23:14.301964-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-26T12:23:14.301964-08:00","close_reason":"Implemented daemon status file writing. Added DaemonStatus struct with capacity/timing/status fields, WriteStatusFile with atomic write (temp + rename), integrated into daemon poll loop. 9 unit tests added, all passing.","labels":["skill:feature-impl","triage:ready"]}
{"id":"orch-go-4kt4","title":"Auto-inject local project ecosystem into spawn context","description":"Spawned agents lack context about Dylan's local projects (glass, beads, kb-cli, orch-go, etc). They try GitHub searches instead of knowing these are local repos. Solution: SPAWN_CONTEXT.md should include ~/.orch/ecosystem.md or similar registry of local projects with descriptions. Supersedes constraint about 'explicitly describe local projects'.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2025-12-28T10:28:20.845858-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-28T15:25:11.024387-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-28T15:25:11.024387-08:00","close_reason":"Already implemented (commit 555e1580)","labels":["triage:ready"]}
{"id":"orch-go-4kwt","title":"Epic: Amnesia-Resilient Artifact Architecture","description":"Design and implement coherent artifact architecture across orchestration ecosystem. Goal: Any fresh Claude can resume work with zero context loss.\n\nThemes identified:\n1. Workspace lifecycle (archival, retention, cleanup)\n2. Knowledge flow (project → global promotion, investigation → decision)\n3. Orchestrator session boundaries (handoffs, synthesis timing)\n4. Cross-artifact relationships (beads ↔ kb ↔ workspace)\n5. Multi-agent coordination (synthesis, conflict detection)\n6. Failure mode capture (post-mortems, structured failure analysis)\n\nSuccess criteria: Minimal artifact set with explicit relationships that fully captures system state.\n\nFoundation: .kb/investigations/2025-12-21-design-deep-pattern-analysis-orchestration-artifacts.md","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2025-12-21T13:36:09.290167-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-21T15:45:59.421177-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-21T15:45:59.421177-08:00"}
{"id":"orch-go-4kwt.1","title":"Investigation: Workspace lifecycle and archival strategy","description":"Questions to answer:\n- When workspaces are cleaned, should SYNTHESIS.md be archived?\n- Should there be .orch/archive/ for completed agent syntheses?\n- What's the retention policy - keep all? successful only? time-based?\n- How does archival interact with kb context discovery?\n\nContext: Currently SYNTHESIS.md is deleted with workspace cleanup, losing session summaries. This may violate session amnesia principle - future Claude can't learn from past agent work patterns.\n\nParent: orch-go-4kwt","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-21T13:36:17.537471-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:50.594684-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:50.594684-08:00","close_reason":"Batch close from orch review"}
{"id":"orch-go-4kwt.2","title":"Investigation: Knowledge promotion paths (project → global)","description":"Questions to answer:\n- When should project .kb/ artifacts promote to global ~/.kb/?\n- What triggers promotion: recurrence across projects? explicit decision?\n- Should investigations that become decisions be archived or remain?\n- How do guides emerge from investigations?\n\nCurrent state: Implicit promotion via copy. No tooling support. Risk of stale duplicates.\n\nParent: orch-go-4kwt","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-21T13:36:20.540821-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:48.629936-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:48.629936-08:00","close_reason":"Batch close from orch review"}
{"id":"orch-go-4kwt.3","title":"Investigation: Orchestrator session boundaries and handoff timing","description":"Questions to answer:\n- When does an orchestrator 'session' end? Context exhaustion? EOD? Project switch?\n- Should SESSION_HANDOFF.md be per-day? per-context-window? per-project?\n- How to handle mid-session project switches?\n- Should there be session-start ritual that reads handoff?\n\nCurrent state: Ad-hoc synthesis files, no standard handoff protocol. skillc has mature pattern.\n\nParent: orch-go-4kwt","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-21T13:36:22.870083-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:49.090078-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:49.090078-08:00","close_reason":"Batch close from orch review"}
{"id":"orch-go-4kwt.4","title":"Investigation: Beads ↔ KB ↔ Workspace relationship model","description":"Questions to answer:\n- Beads tracks WIP, KB tracks knowledge. Where do findings with next-steps live?\n- Should investigations auto-create beads issues for discovered work?\n- Is there a missing 'discovery' artifact between investigation and issue?\n- How should workspace artifacts reference beads/kb and vice versa?\n\nTension: Investigations contain both findings AND action items. Currently manually split.\n\nParent: orch-go-4kwt","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-21T13:36:25.405385-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:47.021266-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:47.021266-08:00","close_reason":"Batch close from orch review"}
{"id":"orch-go-4kwt.5","title":"Investigation: Multi-agent synthesis and conflict detection","description":"Questions to answer:\n- When multiple agents work related issues, who synthesizes findings?\n- Should there be a multi-agent-synthesis artifact type?\n- How to detect when agents' work overlaps or conflicts?\n- Should orchestrator be notified of potential conflicts?\n\nCurrent state: Orchestrator manually synthesizes. No conflict detection. Parallel agents may duplicate work.\n\nParent: orch-go-4kwt","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-21T13:36:27.139649-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:48.926112-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:48.926112-08:00","close_reason":"Batch close from orch review"}
{"id":"orch-go-4kwt.6","title":"Investigation: Failure mode artifacts and post-mortems","description":"Questions to answer:\n- When agents fail/abandon, what artifacts should remain?\n- Should there be structured post-mortem artifact type?\n- How does kn tried --failed relate to formal failure analysis?\n- Can we learn from failure patterns across agents?\n\nCurrent state: Failures disappear. kn captures some learnings but unstructured. No pattern analysis.\n\nParent: orch-go-4kwt","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-21T13:36:29.303152-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:48.045047-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:48.045047-08:00","close_reason":"Batch close from orch review"}
{"id":"orch-go-4kwt.7","title":"Design: Minimal artifact set specification","description":"Synthesis task after investigations complete.\n\nGoal: Define the minimal artifact set that fully captures orchestration system state such that any fresh Claude can resume with zero context loss.\n\nInputs:\n- Workspace lifecycle investigation findings\n- Knowledge promotion paths findings  \n- Session boundary findings\n- Artifact relationship model findings\n- Multi-agent synthesis findings\n- Failure mode findings\n\nOutput: Decision document with artifact taxonomy, relationships, and lifecycle rules.\n\nParent: orch-go-4kwt\nBlocked by: All investigation children","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-21T13:36:32.495332-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:43.375978-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:43.375978-08:00","close_reason":"Batch close from orch review"}
{"id":"orch-go-4kwt.8","title":"Design: Reflection checkpoint pattern for agent sessions","description":"Pattern observed: Agent's most valuable output came from interactive follow-up ('what else do you see?') not autonomous completion.\n\nThe pattern: Autonomous work → Human probe → Deeper synthesis → Richer output\n\nEncode via:\n1. Skill-level: Add reflection phase before completion\n2. Spawn-level: --interactive flag for pause-before-complete\n3. Protocol-level: SPAWN_CONTEXT template update\n4. Artifact-level: Require 'unexplored questions' section in SYNTHESIS.md\n\nKey insight: Agents completing autonomously is efficient but may leave value on the table. Most generative moments happen at boundary between agent work and human judgment.\n\nRelated: SESSION_HANDOFF.md pattern captures 'what next session should explore'\n\nParent: orch-go-4kwt","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-21T13:42:41.895195-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:49.663011-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:49.663011-08:00","close_reason":"Batch close from orch review"}
