{"id":"orch-go-6a0p1","title":"Bug: orch abandon doesn't remove agent from registry","description":"Should remove agent from registry or mark as 'abandoned'.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-01-11T18:30:02.716566-08:00","updated_at":"2026-01-11T19:20:22.162963-08:00","closed_at":"2026-01-11T19:20:22.162963-08:00","close_reason":"Implemented Option 1: Documented registry as spawn-time metadata cache. Added doc comments to Registry struct, deprecated Abandon/Complete/Remove methods. Created decision doc at .kb/decisions/2026-01-12-registry-is-spawn-cache.md. This is expected behavior, not a bug - registry is for lookups, state comes from OpenCode API + beads."}
{"id":"orch-go-6akg","title":"[orch-go] Investigation file claimed work needed but implementation already existed","description":"Investigation files become stale after implementation completes. Case study: .kb/investigations/2025-12-22-inv-update-orch-status-use-islive.md still says 'Next: Implement...' but the work was already done (beads issue orch-go-0cjl closed at 07:37). The kb context search surfaced this stale investigation, leading to a wasted spawn that found nothing to do. Root cause options: (1) investigations don't link to beads issues that implement their recommendations, (2) no lifecycle to mark investigations as 'implemented', (3) kb context doesn't check if related beads issues are closed. Fix: investigations should either link to implementing issue OR have a status field that gets updated when work completes.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2025-12-22T10:28:32.604494-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:48.269862-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-25T22:14:48.269862-08:00","close_reason":"Batch close from orch review"}
{"id":"orch-go-6e5a","title":"Investigate OpenCode session accumulation causing CPU spikes","description":"After extended use, OpenCode accumulates 150+ sessions in memory, causing 370% CPU usage. Need to understand: 1) Are old sessions ever pruned? 2) Should we periodically restart? 3) Can we cap in-memory sessions? Discovered during Dec 25 session when laptop got hot.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2025-12-25T14:32:32.259165-08:00","updated_at":"2025-12-26T10:52:57.832061-08:00","closed_at":"2025-12-26T10:52:57.832061-08:00","close_reason":"Fixed Monitor session accumulation (memory leak) and reconnect goroutine leaks (CPU waste). Added tests for session cleanup, all tests pass.","labels":["skill:investigation","triage:ready"]}
